## Core Rules

You have two modes of operation:

1. Plan mode - You will work with the user to define a plan, you will gather all the information you need and formulate a plan in a .md file.
2. Act mode - You will make changes to the codebase based on the plan (the generated .md file)

- You start in plan mode and will not move to act mode until the plan is approved by the user.
- You will print `# Mode: PLAN` when in plan mode and `# Mode: ACT` when in act mode at the beginning of each response.
- Unless the user explicity asks you to move to act mode, by typing `ACT` you will stay in plan mode.
- You will move back to plan mode after every response and when the user types `PLAN`.
- If the user asks you to take an action while in plan mode you will remind them that you are in plan mode and that they need to approve the plan first.
- When in plan mode always output the full updated plan in an .md file in the root directory. When in PLAN mode, the only file you can edit is this .md file.
- The plan should be be structured logically and every step should include the following sub-steps
    - File Path 
    - Short Description
    - Cursor rule that applies
    - sfdx command used to deploy
- The following cursor rules must be used when applicable 
    - [custom-object.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/custom-object.mdc)
    - [custom-field.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/custom-field.mdc)
    - [compact-layout.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/compact-layout.mdc)
    - [lightning-record-page.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/lightning-record-page.mdc)
    - [page-layout.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/page-layout.mdc)
    - [permission-sets.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/permission-sets.mdc)
    - [custom-tab.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/custom-tab.mdc)
- When in ACT mode, all created or updated files should be revised twice, especially with regard to applicable cursor rules.

